{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1057"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1057"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.11,0.66,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1057"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"621"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2475"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of a painless swelling in her neck. The swelling has shown little evidence of change in size. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a recent migrant from the Philippines. She is a non-smoker, does not drink alcohol, and has never used recreational drugs. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An obvious swelling is visible in the right supraclavicular region (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteomyelitis of the clavicle","Epidermoid cyst","Scrofula","Carcinoma of the thyroid","Branchial cyst"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a chronic, painless neck swelling, which is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Escrofula\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as cervical tuberculous lymphadenitis or \u0027The King\u0027s Evil\u0027. Scrofula is the most common extrapulmonary presentation of tuberculosis (TB). It typically presents as a unilateral mass in the anterior or posterior cervical triangles, submandibular, or supraclavicular nodes. The patient\u0027s recent migration from the Philippines, a country with a high TB burden, further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cutaneous cyst and can occur anywhere on the body. However, it typically presents as a skin-coloured dermal nodule, often with a central punctum. These cysts are usually moveable on palpation and do not typically persist for months without change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the thyroid\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a hard, fixed mass in the anterior neck. While it should be considered in any neck mass, the chronic, painless nature of this swelling and its supraclavicular location make thyroid cancer less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranchial cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are usually located anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. The supraclavicular location of this lesion makes a branchial cyst unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteomyelitis of the clavicle\u003C/strong\u003E may present with local erythema and/or a draining sinus, especially in the context of intravenous drug use. However, this patient has no history of drug use, and the chronic, painless nature of the swelling is inconsistent with osteomyelitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical presentation and the patient\u0027s background, scrofula is the most likely diagnosis. Further investigations, such as fine-needle aspiration for acid-fast bacilli staining and culture, or an interferon-gamma release assay (IGRA) test, would be appropriate to confirm the diagnosis of tuberculosis. Treatment typically involves a multi-drug antitubercular regimen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tuberculosis must always be considered in the differential diagnoses of neck swellings in recent migrants from developing countries.","Scrofula, or cervical tuberculous lymphadenitis, is the most common extrapulmonary presentation of tuberculosis.","Scrofula typically presents as a painless, unilateral neck mass that persists for months."],"references":["Moulis G, Martin-Blondel G. Scrofula, the king\u0027s evil. CMAJ. 2012;184(9):1061. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22371516/","Goldstein BG, Goldstein AO. Overview of benign lesions of the skin. In: UptoDate. [Online]. 2020; cited 2021 Jan 20. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-benign-lesions-of-the-skin","Ross DS. Diagnostic approach to and treatment of thyroid nodule. In: UptoDate. [Online]. 2020; cited 2021 Jan 20. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/diagnostic-approach-to-and-treatment-of-thyroid-nodules","Emerick K. Differential diagnosis of a neck mass. In: UptoDate. [Online]. 2020; cited 2021 Jan 20. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/differential-diagnosis-of-a-neck-mass","Edgington J, Karadsheh M. Osteomylitis Adult. In: Orthobullets [Online]. 2020; cited 2021 Jan 20. Available at: https://www.orthobullets.com/trauma/1057/osteomyelitis--adult"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37803"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1057"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15615"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15615"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/84b35b12-e45d-4555-99d9-cf41662142c3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/84b35b12-e45d-4555-99d9-cf41662142c3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37803"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-05T12:02:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-06T10:06:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1057"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","